{{Infobox news event | title = 2015 Zasyadko mine disaster | image = [[File:Donetsk in Ukraine (-claims).svg|250px]] | caption = Location of Donetsk Oblast in Ukraine | date = 4 March 2015 | time = | place = [[Donetsk Oblast]], [[Ukraine]] | coordinates = | cause = | fatalities = 34<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kyivpost.com/content/ukraine/death-toll-rises-to-34-in-zasiadko-coal-mine-disaster-382782.html|title=Death toll rises to 34 in Zasiadko coal mine disaster|work=KyivPost}}</ref> | reported injuries = 14 }} On 4 March 2015, at around 05:20 local time, there was a [[mining accident]] at the [[Zasyadko coal mine]] in [[Donetsk People's Republic|rebel-held Eastern Ukraine]]. It is suspected to have been caused by a gas explosion.<ref name=bbc>{{cite news|title=Ukraine gas blast: 30 feared dead in Zasyadko coal mine|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-europe-31725243|accessdate=4 March 2015|work=BBC News|date=4 March 2015}}</ref>
Twenty-three people were confirmed dead.<ref name=bbc/> Local rebels claimed a death toll of 30.<ref name=bbc/> There were 230 people in the mine at the time of the explosion.<ref name=bbc/> The Speaker of the Ukrainian parliament, [[Volodymyr Groysman]], called for a minute's silence for 32 fatalities, but later retracted that figure to say that one had died and 30 others' status was unknown.<ref name=bbc/>
Ukrainian President [[Petro Poroshenko]] called for police and rescue services to have access to the mine.<ref name=bbc/>
