'''Acoustic plaster''' is [[plaster]] which contains fibres or aggregate so that it [[absorption (acoustics)|absorbs sound]].
Such plaster is applied in thicknesses of up to 1.5 inches. As compared with other sound insulation, it is easy to apply and is [[fireproof]] but it can be more fragile, being affected by physical stress and humidity.<ref>{{citation | title= Mechanical and Electrical Equipment for Buildings | page=802 | chapter=Building Noise Control | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=EL4nt2VFTZIC&pg=PA802 | publisher=John Wiley and Sons | year=2009}}</ref> Acoustic plaster is used in construction of rooms which require good acoustic qualities such as [[auditorium|auditoria]] and [[library|libraries]].<ref>{{citation | title=Public library buildings | author=Dana Quick McComb | year=1935 | page=57}}</ref><ref>{{citation |title=Time-saver standards |year=1950 | publisher=F. W. Dodge Corp. | chapter=Acoustics of Modern Auditoriums | page=354}}</ref>
Proprietary types of acoustic plaster developed in the 1920s included Macoustic Plaster, Sabinite, Kalite, Wyodak, Old Newark and Sprayo-Flake produced by companies such as [[USG Corporation|US Gypsum]]. These superseded [[felt]]s and [[quilt]]s as a common preference of architects but were difficult to apply and so were superseded in turn by [[acoustic tile]]s.<ref>{{citation |title=Hearing history |author=Mark Michael Smith |page=350 |publisher=University of Georgia Press |year=2004 |isbn=978-0-8203-2582-8}}</ref>
