{{about|a brand of automobiles|the category of small automobiles|Microcar}} {{Expand German|Microcar|date=January 2012}} '''Microcar''' is a French [[microcar]] manufacturer. The company was founded in 1984 as a division of [[Beneteau|Bénéteau group]], a major [[sailboat]] manufacturer. Production moved to a new custom-built factory in September 2000. In September 2008, Microcar was acquired by [[Ligier|Ligier Automobiles]] in a deal backed by the Italian private equity firm 21 Investimenti Partners. The merger created Europe's second-biggest manufacturer of microcars, and largest maker of [[quadricycle]]s, or "sans permis" (license-exempt) vehicles. The Microcar and Ligier brands are to retain their separate identities and production facilities. Phillipe Ligier, son of company founder [[Guy Ligier]], serves as [[Chief executive officer|CEO]] of the expanded Ligier Automobiles.
== Current models == [[File:Microcar M.Go Electric 001.JPG |thumb|Microcar M.Go Electric at the 2008 [[Paris Motor Show]]]] [[File:Microcar MC2.JPG|thumb|Microcar MC1]] The current model range consists solely of the M.Go model introduced in 2009. The M.Go is available in conventional, diesel-engined S, S PACK, MICA, SXI, and Sport trim levels, as well as full electric.
Prior to the M.Go, Microcar was known for their long-running MC Series models, sold as the MC1 and MC2. Both where available as a 2-seat, or 4-seat long wheel base version. The long wheel base being 40mm longer than the short Virgo models. The company also sold a small commercial vehicle called the Sherpa, which was a badge-engineered Ligier X-Pro. The Sherpa was discontinued after the Ligier merger, and the MC has been dropped in favor of the new M.Go. The M.Go was produced with a petrol engine for the UK market.
== Former models == [[File:Microcar Virgo 2 vr.jpg|thumb|Microcar Virgo 2]] * Microcar Family Luxe * Microcar Lyra * Microcar NewStreet, NewStreet Cabriolet * Microcar Pratic Luxe * Microcar Virgo * Microcar Virgo 2 * Microcar Virgo 3 * Microcar Virgo Luxe
== Electric vehicles == From 2006 to 2010, the long-wheelbase version of Microcar's MC Series was used as the basis for the ZENN EV assembled in Canada by [[ZENN Motor Company]] with an electric drivetrain. It was marketed in the U.S. and Canada under the ZENN brand as a "[[Neighborhood Electric Vehicle]]"(NEV), with its top speed governed to {{convert|25|mph||abbr=on}}. Microcar began distributing the ZENN in Europe during 2007 under its own brand, as the Microcar ZENN. ZENN Motor purchased engineless, rolling chassis from Microcar and installed their own electric motor and drivetrain. The ZENNs retailed for $16,900 while actual cost was $65,000. Microcar brought electric vehicle production fully in-house with the M.Go Electric in 2009, and ZENN ceased production of its MC-based vehicle in 2010.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.auto123.com/en/news/green-wheels/canadas-maya-300-the-first-lithium-ion-full-electric-car-sold-in-north-america?model=MAYA+300&make=ELECTROVAYA&artid=105281&pg=2 |title=Canada's Maya 300: the first lithium-ion full electric car sold in North America! - Green Wheels |publisher=Auto123 |date=2009-02-20 |accessdate=2011-11-05}}</ref>
