{{Infobox power station | name = Olmedilla Photovoltaic Park | name_official = Parque Fotovoltaico Olmedilla de Alarcón | image = | image_size = | image_caption = | image_alt = | location_map = Spain | location_map_size = | location_map_caption = | coordinates = {{coord|39|37|43|N|02|04|37|W|type:landmark|display=inline,title}} | coordinates_ref = | country = Spain | location = [[Olmedilla de Alarcón]] | status = O | construction_began = | commissioned = July 2008 | decommissioned = | cost = €384&nbsp;million | owner = | operator = | solar_type = PV | ps_units_operational = 270,000 | solar_csp_heliostats = | solar_site_area = | ps_electrical_capacity = 60&nbsp;[[Megawatts|MW]]<sub>p</sub> | ps_electrical_cap_fac = | ps_annual_generation = 87.5 [[GWh]] | website = [http://www.nobesol.com/?seccion=4&subseccion=2&contenido=40 www.nobesol.com] | extra = }} The '''Olmedilla Photovoltaic Park''' is a 60-[[megawatt]] (MW) [[photovoltaic power plant]], located in [[Olmedilla de Alarcón]], Spain. When completed in July 2008, it was the [[List of photovoltaic power stations#World's largest photovoltaic power stations|world's largest]] power plant using [[photovoltaic]] technology.<ref name=mims> {{cite news | url= http://www.scientificamerican.com/slideshow.cfm?id=10-largest-renewable-energy-projects&photo_id=ACAC0F2E-EC36-52B7-F3F55FE60D5CE59C | title= Slide Show: The World's 10 Largest Renewable Energy Projects | first = Christopher | last = Mims | work = Scientific American | date=2009-06-04 | accessdate=2010-12-04}} </ref><ref name=wec> {{cite book | url= http://www.worldenergy.org/publications/survey_of_energy_resources_interim_update_2009/solar_energy/1816.asp | title= Survey of Energy Resources Interim Update 2009 | chapter = Solar Energy Country Notes update | publisher = [[World Energy Council]] | year = 2009 | accessdate=2010-12-04}} </ref>
